<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The third plan element_Gaps, Barriers, and Incentives_
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
will concentrate on identifying gaps in environmental technology 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
development in order to stimulate technology innovation and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
create a national climate supportive of such innovation. Typical 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
projects will work on institutional, legislative, and tax changes 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that can stimulate support for development and use of improved 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
environmental technologies. The U.S. Department of Commerce is a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
key participant in several of these efforts, along with industry 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
and other regulatory agencies. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The fourth plan component_Improving Competitiveness of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
U.S. Environmental Technologies may also contribute to the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
development and commercialization of technologies relevant to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
further progress in the South Coast, but the primary focus of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this activity is to promote use of U.S. technologies and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
expertise to solve international environmental problems. Initial 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
funding for this plan area is $12 million. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

