<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
3
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
) Clean Car Initiative. On September 29, 1993, President Clinton and Vice President 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Gore announced the ``Clean Car Initiative,'' an historic 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
cooperative effort between the U.S. automakers, the Department of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Energy, the Department of Defense, and EPA. The primary goal of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this initiative is to develop an ultra fuel efficient, safe, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
clean vehicle by the year 2000. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
To implement this goal, industry and government engineering 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
teams will undertake research projects in three categories: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Technologies that can lead to near-term improvements in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
automobile efficiency, safety, and emissions
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
_research in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
this area will include efforts to develop lightweight, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recyclable materials and catalysts for reducing exhaust 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
pollution. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Research that could lead to production prototypes of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vehicles capable of up to three times greater fuel 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
efficiency
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
_projects will include fuel cells and advanced 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
energy storage systems such as ultracapacitors, to produce 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
more fuel-efficient cars that are affordable, meet or exceed 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
current safety standards, and retain the performance and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
comfort available today. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Advanced manufacturing techniques to make it easier to get 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
new product ideas into the marketplace quickly
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
_this 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
effort will involve computer-based design and testing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
systems and automation and control systems. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In support of the Clean Car Initiative, both the U.S. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
automakers and the major utility companies throughout the country 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
are striving to develop inexpensive high energy battery 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technology_a technology that will be applicable to virtually all 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
types of mobile sources. Various projects are underway to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
develop and perfect engines that operate on alternative cleaner 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
burning fuels or utilize fuel cells. The application of 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
regenerative breaking technology to motor vehicles is being 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
studied for light duty vehicles and is even being implemented in 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
a limited number of heavy duty vehicles. Hybrid electric 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
vehicles utilizing both electric and clean burning combustion 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technology are being developed and tested to demonstrate their 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
potential in-use capabilities. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
EPA is also engaged in several other motor vehicle-related 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technological advancement initiatives. For example, EPA is 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
undertaking a regulatory process to introduce improved vapor 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
recovery technologies to automobiles for use during the refueling 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
process. Finally, expected improvements in remote sensing 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
technology may enable inspection programs to more clearly 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
identify in-use high-emitters. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(c) 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
SCAQMD Technology Advancement Office. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In addition to these federally managed programs and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
projects, EPA has provided assistance to the SCAQMD's critically 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
important Technology Advancement Office (TAO). Since its 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
inception in 1987, the TAO has supported research, development, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
demonstration, and commercialization of advanced emissions 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
control technologies and clean fuels.
<FOOTCITE>32</FOOTCITE>
 EPA intends to 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
contribute continued support for the TAO and anticipates that 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
many of the new stationary and mobile source control technologies 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
needed for eventual attainment will derive from the TAO's 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
research efforts. EPA expects to incorporate the results of the 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
SCAQMD's projects in the design of new technology measures issued 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in the future under the section 182(e)(5) provision. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

